A change-of-basis matrix represents the identity map between two bases $B$ and $D$ of a vector space $V$. It allows you to convert the representation of a vector from one basis to another. Specifically, if $\mathsf{Rep}_B(\vec{
u})$ is the representation of a vector $\vec{
u}$ with respect to basis $B$, then the change-of-basis matrix $\mathsf{Rep}_{B,D}(\mathsf{id})$ can be used to find its representation $\mathsf{Rep}_D(\vec{
u})$ with respect to basis $D$ through the equation $\mathsf{Rep}_{B,D}(\mathsf{id})\,\mathsf{Rep}_B(\vec{
u}) = \mathsf{Rep}_D(\vec{
u})$.
